name: varun prakash
review_text: Bhojtal, also known as Upper Lake, is a large lake which lies on the western side of the capital city of Madhya Pradesh, Bhopal, India. It is a major source of drinking water for the residents of the city, serving around 40% of the residents with nearly 30 million imperial gallons (140,000 m3) of water per day.Bada talaab, along with the nearby Chhota Talaab, meaning small lake in Hindi, constitute Bhoj Wetland, which is now a Ramsar site.According to the local folklore, Bhojtal is said to have been built by the Paramara Raja Bhoj during his tenure as a king of Malwa (1005-1055). He is also said to have established the city of Bhopal (also named after him, then as Bhojpal) to secure the eastern frontier of his kingdom. There is a legend why they built the lake. Once king Bhoj suffered from skin disease and all Vaidyas (Doctors) failed to cure him. Then, one day a saint told the king to build a tank to combine 365 tributaries and then have a bath in it to wipe out the skin disease. Bhoj called upon his engineers to build up a huge tank. They spotted a place near river Betwa, which was 32 km away from Bhopal. It was found that it has only 359 tributaries. A Gond Commander Kalia fulfilled this shortage. He then gave the address of an invisible river. After merging the tributaries of this river the number 365 was completed.The lake was created by constructing an earthen dam across the Kolans River. An eleven gate dam called the Bhadbhada dam was constructed at Bhadbhada in 1965 at the southeast corner of the Lake, and now controls the outflow to the river Kaliasote.The lake was known as the Upper Lake or Bada Talab (Big Pond) until March 2011 it was renamed to Bhojtaal in honour of the Great King Raja Bhoj who built it.A huge statue of Raja Bhoj, standing with sword, was also installed on a pillar on one corner of the lake to cement the name of Bhopal as the city of lakesBhojtal is situated on the west central part of Bhopal city and is surrounded by Van Vihar National Park on the south, human settlements on the east and north, and agriculture fields on the west.It has an area of 31 km2, and drains a catchment or watershed of 361 km2. The watershed of the Upper Lake is mostly rural, with some urbanized areas around its eastern end. The Kolans was formerly a tributary of the Halali River, but with the creation of the lake using an earthen dam and a diversion channel, the upper reach of the Kolans River and Bada Talaab now drain into the Kaliasote River.Since the construction of the lake in the 11th century, Bhopal city has grown around it. The people are religiously and culturally attached to the lakes. The lakes meet their needs of water supply and they wash clothes in them (very harmful for the lake ecosystem), cultivate water chestnut in Bhojtal and lotus in Chhota Talaab. The idols of gods and goddesses are also immersed in the lake during religious festivals, though the local administration is advising devotees not to do so. The Takia island in Upper lake has a tomb of the Shah Ali Shah, which has religious and archaeological significance.The fishing rights to Bhopal have been given on long lease by the Bhopal Municipal Corporation to a co-operative consisting of some 500 fishermen families. Fishing is mainly done on its south-eastern shores. The lake also serves as the source of water for irrigating a large area. There are 87 villages in its catchment area in the Bhopal as well as Sehore districts. Agriculture is the main source of livelihood for people in these areas and most farmers have livestock as well. While some farmers have large landholdings, many farmers are small and marginal farmers with only a few acres of land.Bhojtal attracts tourists due to its scenery. The National Sailing School was established at the Boat Clubon its eastern side. This club offers various water sports such as kayaking, canoeing, rafting, water skiing, parasailing etc. A number of operators provide facilities for exciting trips by sail, paddle and motor boats.Van Vihar National Park, situated on the south-eastern of lake

review_text: Bhopal is also known as the city of lakes. Therefore, it is the top destination in the city for the visitors throughout the year. Raja Bhoj, the Parmara King, who ruled the Malwa empire during 1010 - 1055 CE, built this lake during his reign, who is also credited to establish this city which is now the capital of Madhya Pradesh. As a token of honour, his statue is also established in the lake. Apart from rich history, this lake is also an important water body not only for the residents of Bhopal for whom this is a water reservoir, but also ecologically for the environment due to which it has been included in the Ramsar list of Wetlands. One can often find people especially during sunrise and sunset, relaxing and enjoying the cool breeze and the view.

name: R Raza
review_text:
A Tranquil Oasis in the Heart of Bhopal: Upper Lake

Bhopals Upper Lake is a true gem, a serene oasis that captures the heart and soul of this vibrant city. Spanning approximately 31 square kilometers, this expansive water body is a testament to natures beauty and urban planning, making it a must-visit destination for locals and tourists alike.

The Upper Lakes most striking feature is its breathtaking natural beauty. Surrounded by lush greenery, it provides a picturesque backdrop for leisurely walks, picnics, or boat rides. The calm waters reflect the changing colors of the sky, creating stunning sunsets that are nothing short of mesmerizing. Its a perfect spot for photographers and nature enthusiasts seeking tranquility amidst city life.

Boating on the Upper Lake is an absolute delight. Renting a paddle-boat or a rowboat is a popular activity, allowing visitors to explore the lake at their own pace. As you gently glide across the water, youll be treated to picturesque views of the cityscape, as well as numerous migratory birds that call the lake home. Birdwatchers will appreciate the rich avian diversity that graces the lakes shores.

For those seeking a touch of history, the Upper Lake offers a glimpse into Bhopals past with the Shahpura and Kamla Park areas nearby. These parks are ideal for a leisurely stroll or a family outing, complete with well-maintained gardens and play areas for children.

The Upper Lake is not just a place of natural beauty; its also a hub for cultural and recreational activities. The annual Sail Bhopal event showcases sailboat races, attracting sailing enthusiasts from across the country.

What makes the Upper Lake truly special is its role as a green lung for Bhopal. It plays a vital role in maintaining the citys ecological balance, providing clean air and a habitat for a diverse range of wildlife.

In conclusion, Bhopals Upper Lake is a treasure that embodies the perfect blend of nature, culture, and recreational opportunities. Whether youre looking for a peaceful escape, a place to bond with family and friends, or a dose of natural beauty within the city limits, the Upper Lake is a destination that will leave you rejuvenated and inspired by the wonders of the natural world. A visit here is more than just a trip; its an experience that lingers in your heart long after youve left its shores.

name: Hari Om Choure
review_text:
Upper Lake Bhopal: Where Tranquility Meets Natures Splendor in a Serene Oasis

Nestled amidst the picturesque landscape of Bhopal, the Upper Lake stands as a tranquil oasis, captivating visitors with its pristine beauty and serene ambiance. This expansive water body, also known as Bada Talab, not only serves as a lifeline for the city but also offers a sanctuary of peace and tranquility to all who behold its enchanting allure.

Stretching over an area of approximately 36 square kilometers, the Upper Lake is one of the largest artificial lakes in India, seamlessly blending the marvels of human engineering with the bounties of nature. Its shimmering azure waters, gently caressed by the surrounding hills, create a soothing panorama that captivates the senses and rejuvenates the soul.

The allure of the Upper Lake lies not only in its natural splendor but also in the myriad recreational activities it offers. Boating enthusiasts can navigate the tranquil waters, feeling a sense of liberation as they glide along the lakes surface, surrounded by lush greenery and a cool breeze. The rhythmic strokes of oars or the gentle hum of motorboats echo across the water, creating a symphony of tranquility.

As the sun begins to set, painting the sky with hues of gold and orange, the Upper Lake transforms into a canvas of captivating beauty. The reflections of the vibrant colors on the placid waters create a breathtaking spectacle, leaving visitors spellbound by natures artistry.

The Upper Lake is not just a haven for nature lovers but also a sanctuary for a rich biodiversity. It is home to various species of birds, providing a habitat for migratory and resident avifauna. Birdwatchers can spot an array of feathered wonders, from graceful herons to vibrant kingfishers, creating a harmonious blend of colors and melodies.

Surrounding the Upper Lake, lush green gardens and verdant hills add to the idyllic charm of the setting. The tranquility of the lake is further enhanced by the presence of several parks and walking trails, inviting visitors to immerse themselves in the lap of nature. It is a cherished escape for those seeking solace, whether through a leisurely stroll or simply finding a peaceful spot to sit and contemplate the beauty around them.

The Upper Lake in Bhopal is not merely a body of water; it is a sanctuary that offers respite from the bustling city life, a place where one can reconnect with nature and find solace in its embrace. Its ethereal beauty, serene ambiance, and abundant natural treasures make it a cherished gem of Bhopal, inviting all who visit to experience a tranquil haven amidst natures splendor.

Bhojtal Lake is also known as the Upper Lake and is situated in Bhopal. It is located in the vicinity of several other famous tourist attractions. The places to visit near Bhojtal Lake are Lower Lake, Van Vihar, Indira Gandhi Rashtriya Manav Sangrahalaya, Gohar Mahal, etc.

review_text:
Upper Lake Bhopal, also known as Bhojtal, is a breathtakingly beautiful water body located in the heart of Bhopal city in India.

The first thing that strikes me about Upper Lake Bhopal is its sheer size. It is one of the largest man-made lakes in India, covering an area of approximately 31 square kilometers. The lake is fed by several small streams and is surrounded by lush green forests, creating a picturesque landscape that is simply mesmerizing.

The crystal-clear waters of the lake offer a variety of recreational activities for visitors to enjoy. Boating, kayaking, and paddle boating are popular activities, allowing visitors to explore the lake and take in its natural beauty. The surrounding forests provide a serene backdrop for nature walks and hikes, making Upper Lake Bhopal an ideal destination for outdoor enthusiasts.

For those interested in the history and culture of the region, Upper Lake Bhopal offers several notable attractions. The Kamla Park, situated on the eastern shore of the lake, is home to several ancient statues and temples, dating back to the 11th century. The park also features a musical fountain that is a popular attraction for visitors.

Overall, Upper Lake Bhopal is a must-visit destination for anyone traveling to Bhopal. The breathtaking natural beauty, serene atmosphere, and range of recreational activities make it an ideal destination for families, couples, and solo travelers alike.

review_text:
Upper Lake, also known as Bhojtal, is a large lake located in Bhopal, the capital city of the Indian state of Madhya Pradesh. The lake is one of the major sources of drinking water for the city, as well as a popular recreational destination for locals and tourists alike.

The lake was created in the 11th century by Raja Bhoj, a king who ruled the region at that time. It is surrounded by hills and forests, making it a beautiful and tranquil setting for a variety of activities, including boating, fishing, and picnicking.

One of the main attractions of Upper Lake is its stunning sunsets, which can be enjoyed from the numerous viewpoints and parks around the lake. Visitors can also take a boat ride on the lake to get a closer look at the beautiful surroundings and the numerous small islands that dot the lake.

The lake is also home to several important historical and religious sites, including the Bhojeshwar Temple, which is dedicated to Lord Shiva and is believed to have been built by Raja Bhoj himself. The temple is known for its impressive lingam, a representation of Lord Shiva, which is one of the largest in the world.

Overall, Upper Lake is a beautiful and serene destination that offers something for everyone, whether you are looking for a peaceful retreat or an adventurous outing. It is a must-visit destination for anyone traveling to Bhopal or the surrounding region.

name: Sourabh Saini
review_text:
Formerly known as Upper Lake. It is a large lake located on the western edge of Bhopal, the capital of Madhya Pradesh, India. It is a major source of drinking water for the citys residents, providing approximately 30 million imperial gallons (140,000 m3) of water per day to approximately 40% of the residents. The Big Pond, along with the nearby Chhota Pond, has Meaning small lake in Hindi, it forms the Bhoj Wetland, now a Ramsar site.
According to local folklore, Bhojtal was built by the Parmar king Bhoj during his tenure as the king of Malwa (1005-1055). He is also said to have founded the city of Bhopal (named after him, then also known as Bhojpal) to secure the eastern border of his kingdom. There is a legend as to why he created the lake. Once King Bhoj suffered from a skin disease and all the vaidyas (doctors in English) failed to cure him. Then, one day a saint asked the king to build a pond to join 365 tributaries and then bathe in it to cure skin diseases. Bhoj called upon his engineers to build a huge tank. He found a place near Betwa river, which was 32 km from Bhopal. It was found that it has only 359 tributaries. Kalia, a Gond commander, filled this gap. Then he gave the address of an invisible river. By including the tributaries of this river the number was 365.

The lake was created by constructing an earthen dam on the Kolan River. An eleven gate dam called Bhadbhada Dam was constructed in 1965 at the south-east corner of the lake at Bhadbhada, and now controls the outflow of the Kaliyasot River.

The lake was known as Upper Lake or Bada Talab (Big Pond) until March 2011, when it was renamed Bhojtal in honor of the great king Raja Bhoj. To establish Bhopal as the City of Lakes A huge statue of Raja Bhoj standing with a sword on a pillar was also installed at one corner of the lake.

name: Swapnil Gupta
review_text:
The Lower Lake along with the Upper Lake forms the Bhoj Wetland, and is said to date all the way back to 1794. Sitting on the east of the Upper Lake, this lake is a great destination for a day-out. It is open everyday from 9 am until 5 pm for visitors. An amazing place to get some peace of mind.
The fishing rights to Bhojtal have been given on long lease by the Bhopal Municipal Corporation to a co-operative consisting of some 500 fishermen families. Fishing is mainly done on its south-eastern shores. The lake also serves as the source of water for irrigating a large area. There are 87 villages in its catchment area in the Bhopal as well as Sehore districts. Agriculture is the main source of livelihood for people in these areas and most farmers have livestock as well. While some farmers have large landholdings, many farmers are small and marginal farmers with only a few acres of land.
The other major attraction close to the lake is the Bhopal Zoo on the bank of the lake. This makes the lake a complete entertainment location for all visitors. The zoo is kept in quite natural way.
The Lower Lake does not have any fresh water source; it receives seepage water from the Upper Lake and drainage from 28 sewage-filled nullahs.[4] It drains into the Patra rivulet, which joins Halali River, a small tributary of the Betwa River.

There is a lot of Boating options available in the Lake like Paddle Boat, Steamer speed boat, fishing boats and cruise. The cruise can accomodate around 80-100 persons at a time the charges are also reasonable. In short Upper lake is the Major Tourist attraction in Bhopal city for local as well as tourists. If you are going to Bhopal dont forget to see this large man-made lake.

name: GREEDY PIG
review_text:
Bhopal, known as the City of Lakes, has natural as well as man-made lakes. The two main lakes, known as the Upper and the Lower Lake, were constructed in the 11th century and the city has since grown around them. Take a tour of the old part of the city, feast your eyes on its past aristocratic splendour - visit the palaces and the bustling marketplace known locally as the Chowk, where you will find the grand old mosques of Bhopal - the Jama Masjid, Moti Masjid and the Taj-ul-Masjid.

While in Bhopal you must visit the Rock Shelters of nearby Bhimbetka and the Stupa at Sanchi. Best time to visit - Between November and February, the winters are not so harsh and sight seeing will be a pleasure.

name: Ashay Anand
review_text: Upper Lake is the Heart of Bhopal. Bhopal is the city of lakes and Upper Lake is the crown jewel of all the lakes Bhopal has. It looks like an endless ocean from some of its viewing points. Add to it, its importance. Many major landmarks of Bhopal including the Chief Ministers Residence, Van Vihar National Park, Prominent hotels and restaurants like Imperial Sabre, Lake View Ashoka, Winds & Waves etc. are located at the circumference of the lake. Its not just a place for sight seeing, it has delicious eateries for street food lined on its corners, it has restaurants with the view of the lake, cycling facilities, wide pedestrian paths for walking along the lakeside, beautification props like train engine, tank and many such highlights for kids and visitors. Most famous of all is the lakes boat club with dozens of paddle boats, motor boats and a cruise boat for parties. Upper Lake also facilitates competitive water sports for athelets and paramilitary and military sports and is a hub for kayaking and sailing competitors.

Really a remarkable place to enjoy , a very big fresh water body with a lot of activities - sight seeing , water splashing , Power boat  , peddlers boat and etc. , small earth  spots with greenery were just eye catching and soothing to eyes .
I was staying there in hotel noor-us-sabah a wellcome heritage hotel just along side of the lake . View from the hotel was excellent and beyond comparable & hotel a very nice one , once was the palace belonging to Nawab of Bhopal now converted into the wellcome groups heritage hotel  , menu and food from breakfast to dinner was really good deserve 9* out of 10*.
Its a great picnic spot with a great number of activities to enjoy with some strict safety norms as if water  is biggest friend then it is the greatest foe also . No one should dare to challenge the mighty resources to the maximum,
it may certainly demand a price which is unimaginable .
But my overall experience was very best and unforgettable .
I wish to be there again and again , though I have not been there again due to my personal circumstances but I will certainly go to this place if covid-19 is not stalling me .
I will  certainly recommend this place to others ......

name: Nitesh kumar
review_text:
This is a historic lake, aged more than 1000 years old. It was made by Raja Bhoj (the mighty king)

In fact the name of the city, Bhopal also derived from the word "BhojTal" meaning tal (lake) of Bhoj

Apart from the historic importance of the place, the present scenic beauty is awesome & well managed by government to make this a tourist spot. This brings lot of revenue to the people living near by & to the government as well.
One round of boating  in the lake made my evening, crossing through the VIP road on the one periphery of the lake gives a full view of it as well as the huge statue to Raja Bhoj.
A must visit place for all the pille visiting Bhopal.

Bhojtal is situated on the west central part of Bhopal city and is surrounded by Van Vihar National Park on the south, human settlements on the east and north, and agriculture fields on the west. It has an area of 31 km2, and drains a catchment or watershed of 361 km2. The watershed of the Upper Lake is mostly rural, with some urbanized areas around its eastern end. The Kolans was formerly a tributary of the Halali River, but with the creation of the lake using an earthen dam and a diversion channel, the upper reach of the Kolans River and Bada Talaab now drain into the Kaliasote River.

review_text: The oldest manmade lake in the country, it is known as Bada Talaab or the big lake. The Lake is constructed on the Kolas River and it is believed that King Bhoj's skin disease was cured by the huge lake he built. It is a major source of drinkable water for the residents of the city. Bhojtal was built by Raja Bhoj during his tenure as a king of Malwa (1005-1055). He established the city of Bhopal (also named after him, then as Bhojpal) to secure the eastern frontier of his kingdom. The lake was created by constructing an earthen dam across the Kolans River.

name: Anju Bhatnagar & muSAFIR & U
review_text: The main attraction of Bhopal city is the upper lake. The lake is also known as Bhojtal. It is one of the most amazing lake I've seen. It is said that it is one of the oldest human made lake in the country. The lake is the primary source of water for the residents. The lake looks beautiful in all the seasons but during rains the view is spectacular. You can enjoy a boat ride or take a walk around the lake or feel the beauty and cool breeze while sitting near by or click some amazing pictures, do here whatever you want to do. You can also enjoy water sports here.A lot of people come here to enjoy in morning or evening or even at late nights. The sunset and sunrise is very beautiful here. You can see some beautiful and rare birds here as the lake supports more than 100 species of flora and fauna. There are some good restaurants near the lake where you can find great food in a nice ambiance while enjoying the mesmerising view of the lake.

Bhojtal

Bhojtal, formerly known as Upper Lake, is a large lake which lies on the western side of Bhopal. It is a major source of drinking water for the residents of the city, serving around 40% of the residents.

name: lokesh patil
review_text:
Upper lake or Bada talab or Bhojtal is the most significant lake of Bhopal.
Upper lake or bada talab is one of the most important tourist spot in Bhopal.
The lake was built by Raja Bhoj in 11th century. It is spread in area of around 36 kms and serves to 40% residents of Bhopal by supplying water.
Upper lake is surrounded by Van Vihaar in south and human settlements in North and East parts. The lake on the southeast direction has lower lake which was built afterwards.
The lake, infact both lakes support flora and fauna and the Van vihar in south part features animals in natural habitat on one side and scenic beauty of the lake on one side.
The lake has a huge statue of Raja Bhoj standing with sword at one corner of the lake in the honour of the Great King Raja Bhoj.

name: Kushagra Chawda
review_text:
The upper Lake is the part of the big lake in Bhopal. The lower Lake is joined to the upper Lake and a small land mass divides them, hence the name.

The upper Lake is a nice point and should be in your must visit lists of Bhopal. The drive itself is very nice with the lake on one side and a lush green on the other. There are several spots near the lake which can be used if you want to avoid heavy crowded places. The city municipal corporation has also built a beautiful sign that read  the city of lakes . At night, the sign lights up and it is very beautiful.

If you want you can go the lake directly. There are ducks and swans which you can feed. there are also boat rides and cruise drives which tourists can enjoy.

If not, you visit one of the restaurants on the hill side. You can devour quality food with an exceptional view. In fact one of the scenes of the movie arakshan starring Deepika Padukone and saif Ali khan was shot here, I dont remember which restaurant is it, if anybody knows please reply it in the replies to the comment section.

name: vinay prajapati
review_text: Bhojtal was built by Parmar king Bhoj between 1005 and 1055. Raja Bhoj built Bhopal (earlier known as Bhojpal). The purpose of building Bhopal was to strengthen its eastern defense line. According to a legend, the purpose of building Bhojtal was that King Bhoj was suffering from a skin disease. Which many physicians and doctors could not cure, then a saint told the king to make a pond which would contain the water of 365 tributaries. By bathing in it, his extreme disease will be cured. Raja Bhoj asked his engineers to build a pond. Raja Bhojs engineers thought it appropriate to carry out this work on Betwa river, which is 32 kilometers away from Bhopal. The dilemma was that Betwa had a total of 359 tributaries. Then Kali, a Gond Sena chief, removed this shortcoming, He told about some other invisible rivers, by connecting which the total tributaries became 365 and this pond was formed.

name: Kamlesh Kumar I Kamlesh Kamlesh Kumar Dahiya Dahiya
Neal Nagar
review_text:
The capital city of Madhya Pradesh holds a significant number of lakes hence widely known as Bhopal the city of lakes. Upper Lake is the most significant lake of Bhopal commonly known as the Bhojtal. It's the oldest human-made lake in the country that lies on the west of Bhopal. The locals also call it Bada Talab. Serving around 30 million gallons of water the lake is a primary source of potable water to the residents of the city.

This beautiful vast water body was named after King Bhoj who built the lake across Kolans River in the 11th-century. According to the folklore, the king constructed this humongous lake to cure himself of his skin disease. The pillar on one corner of the lake holds the statue of Raja Bhoj. The Upper Lake is separated from the lower lake by an overbridge called Pul Pukhta.

Since agriculture is the main source of livelihood for people of Bhopal, the lake is the primary source of water for irrigation. On the eastern side of the lake, the boat club was established offering some water sports for the visitors such as parasailing, kayaking, canoeing, rafting etc. Within its vicinity lies the scenic Kamala Park. The royal garden is flooded with tourists and visitors during the peak seasons since it?s a hub for all adventure enthusiasts. The boat club, sunset, aquarium serenaded by the cool breeze of Bhopal is a perfect getaway.

review_text: According to the local folklore, Bhojtal is said to have been built by the Paramara Raja Bhojduring his tenure as a king of Malwa (1005-1055). He is also said to have established the city of Bhopal (also named after him, then as Bhojpal) to secure the eastern frontier of his kingdom. There is a legend why they built the lake. Once king Bhoj suffered from skin disease and all Vaidyas (Doctor in English) failed to cure him. Then, one day a saint told the king to build a tank to combine 365 tributaries and then have a bath in it to wipe out the skin disease. Bhoj called upon his engineers to build up a huge tank. They spotted a place near river Betwa, which was 32 km away from Bhopal. It was found that it has only 359 tributaries. A Gond Commander Kalia fulfilled this shortage. He then gave the address of an invisible river. After merging the tributaries of this river the number 365 was completed.[4]

review_text:
The Upper Lake of Bhopal is a huge water reservoir that lies in the Western part of the city. The lake is considered to be the biggest lake in Madhya Pradesh. Seeing this Bada Talaab one goes absolutely speechless. The lake is the major man-made drinking source for the residents of the city.

This beautiful water reservoir is said to have existed since the 11th century. It is has a huge earthen embankment built across the Kolans River. The lake is visited not only for sight-seeing but also for customary beliefs as locals think its waters have the power to heal skin ailments. Apart from this, it is a favourite place among adventure lovers as it offers various sports activities such as paddling, rowing, and motorboats to indulge themselves.

The attraction is a ferry at 7 pm in which music plays you can enjoy a ride of it with friends n family for 45 min in just 100. There is dargah on a small island in middle of lake where you can go. Night view of lake is awesome. Enjoy! Explore more

name: Arindam Sharma
review_text:
Bhojtal, formerly known as Upper Lake, is a large lake which lies on the western side of the capital city of Madhya Pradesh, Bhopal. It is a major source of drinking water for the residents of the city, serving around 40% of the residents with nearly 30 million imperial gallons (140,000 m3) of water per day. Bada talaab, along with the nearby Chhota Talaab, meaning small lake in Hindi, constitute Bhoj Wetland, which is now a Ramsar site.
According to the local folklore, Bhojtal is said to have been built by the Paramara Raja Bhoj during his tenure as a king of Malwa (1005-1055). He is also said to have established the city of Bhopal (also named after him, then as Bhojpal) to secure the eastern frontier of his kingdom. There is a legend why they built the lake. Once king Bhoj suffered from skin disease and all Vaidyas (Doctor in English) failed to cure him. Then, one day a saint told the king to build a tank to combine 365 tributaries and then have a bath in it to wipe out the skin disease. Bhoj called upon his engineers to build up a huge tank. They spotted a place near river Betwa, which was 32 km away from Bhopal. It was found that it has only 359 tributaries. A Gond Commander Kalia fulfilled this shortage. He then gave the address of an invisible river. After merging the tributaries of this river the number 365 was completed.

The lake was created by constructing an earthen dam across the Kolans River. An eleven gate dam called the Bhadbhada dam was constructed at Bhadbhada in 1965 at the southeast corner of the Lake, and now controls the outflow to the river Kaliasote.

The lake was known as the Upper Lake or Bada Talab (Big Pond) until March 2011 it was renamed to Bhojtaal in honour of the Great King Raja Bhoj who built it. A huge statue of Raja Bhoj, standing with sword, was also installed on a pillar on one corner of the lake to cement the name of Bhopal as the city of lakes

In July 2016 :Bhopal Upper Lake dam gates opened so early in July after 38 years.

name: Laxman Kushwah
review_text: The locals call this place as Bara Talab and it happens to be the oldest manmade lake in all of India. Also referred to as Bhojtal as it was King Bhoj who had it built in the 11th century so that he could take a dip in its waters are be cured of a skin disease. Close to it is Kamala Park, the royal garden, a place that tourists flock to and one that cannot be missed out when one is on vacation in Madhya Pradesh. The place is kept clean and the air is fresh making this place a hit with the locals and as well as foreign tourists.

name: Nikhil Mulinti
review_text: Two contiguous human-made reservoirs - the Upper Lake was created in the 11th century by construction of an earthen dam across the Kolans River, and the lower was constructed nearly 200 years ago, largely from leakage from the Upper, and is surrounded by the city of Bhopal. The lakes are very rich in biodiversity, particularly for macrophytes, phytoplankton, zooplankton, both natural and cultured fish species, both resident and migratory birds, insects, and reptiles and amphibians. Since implementation of a management action plan was begun in 1995 with financial support from the government of Japan, a number of bird species have been sighted which had rarely or never before been seen in the region. WWF-India has been of great assistance in preparing the sites designation
